         <abstract>
            <p>Certain critical theorists-notably, Brian Fay-find interpretive theory to be conservative in its effect because its focus on internal standards of rationality, informing political practice, is likely to lead participants to an acceptance of their political situation. In this article, Professor Gibbons argues that not all interpretive theory works that way. There is indeed a form of this theory, the objectivist, in which genuine sources of conservatism may be found. But, then, there is a critical form that avoids unjustified conservatism.</p>
         </abstract>
